## T-B1.6.9: Ignored-test discipline guard — plain `cargo test` must not run heavy N=128 paths

**Target paths**: `crates/gbf-meta-checks/tests/ignored_discipline.rs`

### Background

The pre-commit hook in this project runs `cargo test --workspace --all-features` on every commit. F-B1's heavy gates (T-B1.4.6 N=128 streamed-output, T-B1.5.6 L4 hard gate suite, T-B1.6.2 full-sweep bench) are marked `#[ignore]` so they don't fire on every commit. The review packet's `regen.sh` script runs them deliberately with `cargo test -- --ignored`.

But: nothing prevents a future contributor from removing `#[ignore]` to "unblock CI" or "see if the test still works." The first commit that does this would silently make every subsequent commit run a multi-minute N=128 emulator pass.

### What this bead implements

A meta-test that asserts each named heavy test is still `#[ignore]`d. If someone removes the attribute, this test fires and the pre-commit hook rejects the commit with a clear diagnostic.

### Implementation outline

```rust
// crates/gbf-meta-checks/tests/ignored_discipline.rs
//
// Asserts that the named F-B1 heavy tests carry #[ignore]. If a contributor
// removes #[ignore] from one of these tests, the heavy test would start
// running on every pre-commit hook invocation, blowing CI time.
//
// We discover ignore-status by parsing `cargo test -- --list --format=terse`
// output (or json equivalent). The test runs in <1s.

const HEAVY_TESTS: &[(&str, &str)] = &[
    ("gbf-emu",   "f_b1_l3_streamed_output_matches_reference_n128"),
    ("gbf-bench", "f_b1_l3_records_tile_metrics"),
    ("gbf-emu",   "f_b1_l4_n128_no_frame_service_misses"),
    ("gbf-emu",   "f_b1_l4_liveness_no_progress_frames_bounded"),
    ("gbf-emu",   "f_b1_l4_output_matches_reference"),
    ("gbf-bench", "matmul_bringup_full_n128_run"),
    ("gbf-bench", "matmul_bringup_full_sweep"),
];

#[test]
fn heavy_tests_remain_ignored_in_plain_cargo_test() {
    for (krate, test_name) in HEAVY_TESTS {
        let listing = list_tests_for_crate(krate)
            .unwrap_or_else(|e| panic!("listing {} failed: {}", krate, e));
        let entry = listing.iter().find(|t| t.name.ends_with(test_name))
            .unwrap_or_else(|| panic!(
                "expected heavy test `{}` to exist in `{}`; it is not listed. \
                 Did the test get renamed? Update HEAVY_TESTS.",
                test_name, krate));
        assert!(
            entry.ignored,
            "heavy test `{}::{}` is no longer #[ignore]d. Removing #[ignore] \
             would cause the pre-commit hook to run the full N=128 path on \
             every commit. Re-add #[ignore] or update T-B1.6.9 with explicit \
             rationale.",
            krate, test_name);
    }
}

#[test]
fn cargo_test_without_ignored_does_not_run_heavy_tests() {
    // Synthetic: execute `cargo test -p gbf-emu --no-run` and inspect the
    // built binary's expected runtime; assert ignored discipline holds.
    // (This is an integration test gated behind a feature; the simpler check
    // is the listing-based assertion above.)
}
```

### Logging discipline

When the assertion fails, emit a single structured `tracing::error!` with the offending test name and crate, plus a remediation hint pointing at this bead and the RFC's "long-running test ownership" rule.

### Why this is load-bearing

Without this guard, the heavy gates are protected only by a contributor's memory of the convention. F-B1 is one of the first features in the project to introduce truly heavy tests; the guard establishes the pattern for M1's quantized-kernel tests, M1's oracle tests, and beyond.

### Acceptance gates

```bash
cargo test -p gbf-meta-checks -- heavy_tests_remain_ignored_in_plain_cargo_test
# Synthetic regression test:
cargo test -p gbf-meta-checks -- cargo_test_without_ignored_does_not_run_heavy_tests
```

### RFC reference

`history/rfcs/F-B1-compute-bringup.md` §14 (long-running test ownership), §16.1 (risk: full benchmark too heavy for ordinary tests).

### Dependencies

- T-B1.4.6 (N=128 emu test exists with `#[ignore]`).
- T-B1.5.6 (L4 hard gate suite exists with `#[ignore]`).
- T-B1.6.2 (full-sweep bench exists with `#[ignore]`).

## T-A2.3: MBC5 register semantics

**Target crate**: `gbf-hw`
**Target file(s)**: `gbf-hw/src/mbc5.rs`
**Reference**: `planv0.md` line 1716 ("Pan Docs notes the canonical RAM-enable value is $0A"); Pan Docs §"MBC5".

### Background

MBC5 is the cartridge memory controller for our targets. It exposes four register bands:
- `$0000–$1FFF`: RAMG (RAM enable). Write `$0A` to enable, anything else (canonically `$00`) to disable.
- `$2000–$2FFF`: ROM bank low byte (`BANK1[7:0]`).
- `$3000–$3FFF`: ROM bank high bit (`BANK2[0]`). Together with `BANK1`, gives 9-bit ROM bank number → up to 8 MiB ROM.
- `$4000–$5FFF`: SRAM bank (4-bit, 16 banks of 8 KiB → 128 KiB SRAM).

This task encodes those addresses, the canonical RAM-enable value, and the bit layouts as types.

### Implementation Notes

```rust
pub const MBC5_RAMG_BASE:          u16 = 0x0000;
pub const MBC5_RAMG_END:           u16 = 0x1FFF;
pub const MBC5_BANK1_BASE:         u16 = 0x2000;
pub const MBC5_BANK1_END:          u16 = 0x2FFF;
pub const MBC5_BANK2_BASE:         u16 = 0x3000;
pub const MBC5_BANK2_END:          u16 = 0x3FFF;
pub const MBC5_RAMB_BASE:          u16 = 0x4000;
pub const MBC5_RAMB_END:           u16 = 0x5FFF;

pub const MBC5_RAM_ENABLE_VALUE:   u8 = 0x0A;
pub const MBC5_RAM_DISABLE_VALUE:  u8 = 0x00;

pub enum MbcRegisterClass {
    Ramg,                                     // RAM enable
    Bank1,                                    // ROM bank low byte
    Bank2,                                    // ROM bank high bit
    Ramb,                                     // SRAM bank
}

pub fn classify_mbc_register(addr: u16) -> Option<MbcRegisterClass>;
pub fn rom_bank_address(bank1: u8, bank2: u8) -> u16;     // 0..=511
```

Pan Docs notes a quirk: "relying on other low-nibble-A values [for RAM enable] is not recommended for compatibility." Document this in `MBC5_RAM_ENABLE_VALUE`'s doc comment.

### Acceptance Criteria

```bash
cargo check -p gbf-hw
cargo test -p gbf-hw -- mbc5::register_address_classification    # Each MBC5 address band classifies correctly
cargo test -p gbf-hw -- mbc5::ram_enable_value                    # Canonical $0A
cargo test -p gbf-hw -- mbc5::bank_address_assembly               # bank1/bank2 -> 9-bit bank number
```

### Constitution Checkpoints

- §I.1: `MbcRegisterClass` enum is exhaustive over MBC5's register bands.
- §VI.1: MBC5 semantics live only here; F-A4's BankLease primitives import them.

## T-A4.3: Acquire / release primitives in AsmIR

**Target crate**: `gbf-runtime`
**Target file(s)**: `gbf-runtime/src/banking.rs` (extends T-A4.2)
**Reference**: `planv0.md` line 1631, T-A1.3 builder pseudo-ops.

### Background

This is where the rubber meets the road. `BankLease` (T-A4.1) is just a type; this task implements the AsmIR builders that emit the actual MBC writes + shadow updates. Every other module in the system that needs to switch banks goes through these primitives.

### Implementation Notes

```rust
/// Emit AsmIR for: enable SRAM, write MBC5 RAMG = $0A.
pub fn emit_enable_sram<B: Builder>(b: &mut B);

/// Emit AsmIR for: disable SRAM, write MBC5 RAMG = $00.
pub fn emit_disable_sram<B: Builder>(b: &mut B);

/// Emit AsmIR for: switch to ROM bank N (9-bit). Updates BANK1 + BANK2 + shadow.
pub fn emit_acquire_rom_bank<B: Builder>(b: &mut B, bank: u16);

/// Emit AsmIR for: switch to SRAM bank N (4-bit). Updates RAMB + shadow. Caller responsible for `enable_sram` first.
pub fn emit_acquire_sram_bank<B: Builder>(b: &mut B, bank: u8);

/// Emit a release: by lifetime, this is either a no-op (Slice) or an explicit
/// switch back to a known-safe bank (Manual).
pub fn emit_release<B: Builder>(b: &mut B, lease: &BankLease, return_to: ReturnBank);

pub enum ReturnBank {
    Bank1,                                    // canonical "safe" bank for return
    Manual(u16),
    KeepCurrent,
}
```

Each primitive emits a typed sequence:
1. (optional) `DI` if the runtime configures `InterruptPolicy::ShortCriticalSection`.
2. `LD A, <value>` + `LD (<MBC register>), A`.
3. (optional) Update HRAM shadow: `LD (<HRAM_OFF>), A`.
4. (optional) `EI` to close the critical section.

The `MachineEffect` of these ops is `StoreToMbcRegister` (T-A1.4), which makes them `PrivilegeClass::Privileged` — only sections marked `default_privilege = Privileged` may emit them, and that's exactly the banking module sections. Everyone else uses these helpers.

### Acceptance Criteria

```bash
cargo check -p gbf-runtime
cargo test -p gbf-runtime -- banking::emit_enable_sram_sequence    # Generates expected AsmIR
cargo test -p gbf-runtime -- banking::emit_acquire_rom_bank_sequence
cargo test -p gbf-runtime -- banking::emit_release_returns_to_bank1
cargo test -p gbf-runtime -- banking::all_emits_are_privileged     # Generated AsmIR has Privileged class
```

### Constitution Checkpoints

- §I.1: Privileged emission is gated through these helpers; bypass becomes a section-privilege violation.
- §VI.1: Sole legal MBC write path.

