### Acceptance Criteria

```bash
cargo check -p gbf-hw
cargo test -p gbf-hw -- memory::region_classification         # Every address maps to exactly one region
cargo test -p gbf-hw -- memory::isr_legal_predicate           # Matches Bank0 + HRAM + WRAM
cargo test -p gbf-hw -- memory::region_sizes                  # Each region size matches Pan Docs
```

### Constitution Checkpoints

- §I.1: `MemoryRegion` is exhaustive.
- §VI.1: Memory map constants live only here.

## Agent Instructions

**Target crate**: `gbf-foundation`
**Target file(s)**:
- `gbf-foundation/src/lib.rs` (re-exports)
- `gbf-foundation/src/hash.rs` (Hash256)
- `gbf-foundation/src/cost.rs` (ByteCost)
- `gbf-foundation/src/ids.rs` (all typed IDs)

**Reference**: `history/planv0.md` — grep for these type names throughout the document to see usage patterns.

### Implementation Notes
```rust
// ids.rs — macro-generate newtypes for type safety
macro_rules! typed_id {
    ($name:ident, $inner:ty) => {
        #[derive(Debug, Clone, Copy, PartialEq, Eq, Hash, Serialize, Deserialize)]
        pub struct $name(pub $inner);
        impl From<$inner> for $name { fn from(v: $inner) -> Self { Self(v) } }
    };
}

typed_id!(LayerId, u16);
typed_id!(ExpertId, u16);
typed_id!(BudgetSlotId, u16);

// String-wrapped ids for named entities
macro_rules! string_id {
    ($name:ident) => {
        #[derive(Debug, Clone, PartialEq, Eq, Hash, Serialize, Deserialize)]
        pub struct $name(pub String);
    };
}

string_id!(TargetProfileId);
string_id!(CompileProfileId);
string_id!(TargetFamilyId);
string_id!(CheckpointId);
string_id!(WorkloadId);
```

- Keep it minimal — just newtypes + derives + basic impls.
- Hash256: include `Display` (hex), `FromStr`, `as_bytes()`, `from_bytes()`.
- ByteCost: implement Add, Sub, Display, Ord for comparison.

### Acceptance Criteria
```bash
cargo check -p gbf-foundation                    # Compiles
cargo test -p gbf-foundation                      # Tests pass
cargo clippy -p gbf-foundation -- -D warnings     # Clean
# Compile-time safety test:
# fn takes_layer(id: LayerId) and fn takes_expert(id: ExpertId)
# cannot accidentally pass ExpertId where LayerId is expected
```

### Constitution Checkpoints
- §I.1: THIS IS THE CONSTITUTION IN ACTION — newtypes make invalid states unrepresentable
- §II.3: Macro-generate boilerplate, one canonical pattern
- §II.4: Code is cheap — generate these types, focus energy on the specs they protect

## T-A2.6: Joypad register

**Target crate**: `gbf-hw`
**Target file(s)**: `gbf-hw/src/joypad.rs`
**Reference**: Pan Docs §"Joypad".

### Background

The joypad is read through register `P1` / `JOYP` at `$FF00`. Bit 4/5 select direction-pad vs button-pad reads; bits 0–3 read the column. The runtime joypad reader (F-A5.3) consumes these constants.

### Implementation Notes

```rust
pub const JOYP_REGISTER: u16 = 0xFF00;

pub const JOYP_SELECT_BUTTONS:     u8 = 0b0010_0000;
pub const JOYP_SELECT_DIRECTIONS:  u8 = 0b0001_0000;

// Buttons (when bit 5 = 0):
pub const JOYP_BIT_A:      u8 = 0b0000_0001;
pub const JOYP_BIT_B:      u8 = 0b0000_0010;
pub const JOYP_BIT_SELECT: u8 = 0b0000_0100;
pub const JOYP_BIT_START:  u8 = 0b0000_1000;

// Directions (when bit 4 = 0):
pub const JOYP_BIT_RIGHT: u8 = 0b0000_0001;
pub const JOYP_BIT_LEFT:  u8 = 0b0000_0010;
pub const JOYP_BIT_UP:    u8 = 0b0000_0100;
pub const JOYP_BIT_DOWN:  u8 = 0b0000_1000;

pub enum Button {
    A, B, Select, Start, Up, Down, Left, Right,
}

pub struct ButtonState {
    pub bits: u8,                            // bit i = pressed for Button::ALL[i]
}

impl ButtonState {
    pub fn is_pressed(&self, b: Button) -> bool;
    pub fn just_pressed(prev: Self, cur: Self, b: Button) -> bool;
}
```

Note: button bits in the hardware register are **active-low** (0 = pressed). The `ButtonState` here is the post-decode active-high view; the joypad reader (F-A5.3) inverts.

