    let r2 = lower_compute_bringup(req).unwrap();
    assert_eq!(sha256(&r1.bytes), sha256(&r2.bytes));
    assert_eq!(r1.sym_canonical, r2.sym_canonical);
    assert_eq!(r1.lst_canonical, r2.lst_canonical);
}
```

### What this protects against

| Failure mode                                         | Caught by              |
|------------------------------------------------------|------------------------|
| AsmIR shape changes silently                          | Snapshot test          |
| ROM bytes diverge across host architectures           | Hash-stability test    |
| Lowering becomes non-deterministic                    | Two-runs test          |
| Tracing events become stringly-typed                  | Typed-event capture    |
| `.sym` label naming regresses                         | sym snapshot           |
| Lowering stage skipped (e.g., AsmIR emit but no ROM)  | Event-order assertion  |

### New deps

- This bead now blocks on T-B1.0.9 (typed tracing vocabulary) — was already added at the dep-wiring step.
- This bead now blocks on T-B1.0.8 (test fixtures — `canonical_l1_request()` lives there).

## T-A1.3: Builder eDSL — typed instruction emitter + Db/Dw + pseudo-ops

**Target crate**: `gbf-asm`
**Target file(s)**: `gbf-asm/src/builder.rs`
**Reference**: `planv0.md` §"Assembly eDSL" (line 2046), engineering rule 1 ("All generated executable code originates from `AsmIR` / `Instr` / audited runtime builders, never from ad hoc byte pushes"), engineering rule 10 (`Raw(Vec<u8>)` is an escape hatch, never the default).

### Background

The builder is the API surface that runtime code (F-A5) and compiler-generated code (Epic B) use to emit `AsmIR`. It must be ergonomic enough that runtime authors don't reach for `Raw` and tight enough that the typed invariants from T-A1.1 / T-A1.2 are preserved.

### Implementation Notes

```rust
pub struct Builder {
    section: Section,
    cur_provenance: InstrProvenance,
}

impl Builder {
    pub fn new(role: SectionRole, name: SymbolName) -> Self;
    pub fn emit(&mut self, instr: Instr);
    pub fn db(&mut self, byte: u8);
    pub fn dw(&mut self, word: u16);
    pub fn label(&mut self, name: SymbolName) -> SymbolId;
    pub fn align(&mut self, align: u16);
    pub fn raw(&mut self, bytes: Vec<u8>);              // ESCAPE HATCH — emits a clippy lint
    pub fn with_provenance<R>(&mut self, p: InstrProvenance, f: impl FnOnce(&mut Self) -> R) -> R;

    // Pseudo-ops (lower to underlying Instrs in T-A1.7 encoder or to runtime calls)
    pub fn bank_lease(&mut self, lease: BankLeaseSpec);
    pub fn bank_release(&mut self, lease_id: LeaseId);
    pub fn far_call(&mut self, target: SymbolName, lease_chain: &[LeaseId]);
    pub fn yield_op(&mut self, kind: YieldKind);
    pub fn trace_probe(&mut self, id: TraceProbeId, level: ProbeLevel);
    pub fn assert_bank(&mut self, expected: MbcBankClass, expected_n: u8);

    pub fn finish(self) -> Section;
}
```

The pseudo-ops do **not** emit MBC writes directly. They lower through the `BankLease` ABI (F-A4) which itself uses `Builder::emit`. The encoder (T-A1.7) is what turns the pseudo-op markers into actual byte sequences.

Add a clippy lint or doc warning on `raw()` discouraging its use; CI grep test counts uses across the workspace.

### Acceptance Criteria

```bash
cargo check -p gbf-asm
cargo test -p gbf-asm -- builder::roundtrip               # Build a tiny section, verify Section content matches expectations
cargo test -p gbf-asm -- builder::provenance_recorded     # Every emitted item carries non-default InstrProvenance
cargo test -p gbf-asm -- builder::pseudo_ops_dont_panic    # Each pseudo-op accepts well-formed inputs
# Workspace-wide grep test (run in gbf-test eventually):
# rg "Builder::raw\(" --type rust crates/ | wc -l    # Should be very small (audited list)
```

### Constitution Checkpoints

- §I.1: Builder enforces typed instructions; raw bytes require explicit opt-in.
- §VI.1: Single authoring layer.

